[4] Developmental brain abnormalities
Date: Mon 13 May 2019
Source: The Journal of Neuroscience [edited]
https://www.jneurosci.org/content/39/27/5393.long


ref: Snyder-Keller A, Kramer LD, Zink S, Bolivar V. Mouse strain and sex-dependent differences in long-term behavioral abnormalities and neuropathologies after developmental Zika infection. J Neurosci. 2019; 39(27): 5393-403. doi: 10.1523/JNEUROSCI.2666-18.2019
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Abstract
--------
Exposure of the developing fetus to Zika virus (ZIKV) results in a set of brain abnormalities described as the congenital Zika syndrome. Although microcephaly is the most obvious outcome, neuropathologies such as intracranial calcifications and polymicrogyria can occur in the absence of microcephaly. Moreover, the full impact of exposure on motor, social, and cognitive skills during development remains uncharacterized. We examined the long-term neurobehavioral consequences of neonatal ZIKV exposure in 4 genetically divergent inbred mouse strains (C57BL/6J, 129S1/SvImJ, FVB/NJ, and DBA/2J). Male and female mice were infected on postnatal day 1, considered comparable to exposure late in the 2nd trimester of humans. We demonstrate strain differences in early susceptibility to the virus and the time course of glial reaction in the brain. These changes were associated with strain- and sex-dependent differences in long-term behavioral abnormalities that include hyperactivity, impulsiveness, and motor incoordination. In addition, the adult brains of susceptible mice exhibited widespread calcifications that may underlie the behavioral deficits observed. Characterization of the neuropathological sequelae of developmental exposure to the Zika virus in different immunocompetent mouse strains provides a foundation for identifying genetic and immune factors that contribute to long-term neurobehavioral consequences in susceptible individuals.
Significance statement
Developmental Zika virus (ZIKV) infection is now known to cause brain abnormalities in infants that do not display microcephaly at birth, and the full impact of these more subtle neuropathologies has yet to be determined. We demonstrate in a mouse model that long-lasting behavioral aberrations occur after developmental ZIKV exposure. We compare 4 divergent mouse strains and find that the effects of Zika infection differ greatly between strains, in terms of behavioral changes, sex differences, and the intracranial calcifications that develop in the brains of susceptible mice. These findings provide a foundation for identifying susceptibility factors that lead to the development of abnormal behaviors secondary to ZIKV infection early in life.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[This study provides yet another consequence of fetal Zika virus infection in a mouse model. It will be interesting to see if similar neurobehavioral consequences occur in the early life of children infected with Zika virus in utero but without resulting microcephaly. If these abnormal behaviors do result, it will place additional burdens on the parents of these children and with the schools that will deal with their education. - Mod.TY]

